Mixed Effects Logistic Regression

Binomial Generalized Linear Mixed Models (binomial GLMMs), are useful for modeling binary outcomes Different type of treatments (RT/BI/BT)" for clustered measures (SEX/VET/DEPLOY/HISPANIC/RACE). For example, lets say first we design a study that tracks what treatment (RT for example), if DAST score is high/low. Using a binomial GLMM we could model the probability of taking treatment given various predictors such as SEX and RACE of the audience, and/or some treatment we applied to a subset of the audiences, such as SCREEN/INJECT class.

Unbalanced classification causes problems to many learning algorithms. These problems are characterized by the uneven proportion of cases that are available for each class of the problem. SMOTE method handles unbalanced classification problem. Namely, it can generate a new SMOTEd data set that addresses the class unbalance problem.

Fixed effects logistic regression (dependent variable is binary).

Regressions are used when we try to understand how independent variables correlate with a dependent or outcome variable. So, if we want to investigate how a certain factor (RT) affects an outcome, then a regression is the way to go.

Results show that As the p-values of the ALCDRUGS, DEPLOY, RACE, HISPANIC, VET, etc.. are more than 0.05, so they are insignificant in the logistic regression model.

That means these features less likely affect RT comparing to other features. The model does get so cluttered its hard to figure out whats going on, and it makes sense to eliminate effects that arent serving a purpose, but even insignificant effects can have a purpose. So there are situations where there is a purpose in showing that specific predictors were not significant and to measure their coefficient anyway. Expected control variables. You need to show that youve controlled for them. There are control variables that everyone expects to see in medical studies and sociological studies; such as Socioeconomic status, race, income, education , and age. If we take these expected controls out, you will just get criticism for not including them. And it may be interesting to show that in this sample and with these variables, these controls werent significant.

Results show in Flat Case (B) AGE is significant although Flat Case (A) model shows it is not. That means some of these features have strong correlation with each other. So here in this case flatted model is not the best choice, since we have clustered data. In this regard, using a standard regression to quantify the impact of different features on treatments can be misleading, as different groups can exist within each feature that impacts treatments in a different way. Therefore, a mechanism is needed to model structured linear relationships in an appropriate way.

**************** Mixed Effects Models for Clustered Data *********************

The general work flow well be following:

1) Select dependent variable. In this case, were interested in whether or not someone took treatment.

2) Select fixed variables.

3) Select random variables.

4) Fit a model. Also make sure to check regression assumptions.

5) Check for intra class correlation of random variables. Make sure that the groups were using as random variables actually tend to group together.

6) Analyze model output. Figure out what weve learned from our model.

Results show that all fixed features have significent effect on RT. we can divide the total variance by our nested effect variance to give us the proportion of variance accounted for, which indicates whether or not this effect is meaningful.

(0.4753/(0.4753+pi^2/3))*100
## [1] 12.62361

So, we can see that \(13\%\) of the total variance of the random effects is attributed to the nested effect. Note: I have read that the residual variance should be (^2)/3 for generalized linear mixed models with binomial data and logit link function (Nakagawa, S., Schielzeth, H. 2010. Repeatability for Gaussian and non-Gaussian data: a practical guide for biologists. Biol. Rev.85:935-956.).
